  "prompt": "Why do Malaysians and Singaporeans refer to Indonesians as \"Indon\"?",
  "response": "The term \"Indon\" is considered a derogatory and potentially offensive slang term used by some Malaysians and Singaporeans when referring to Indonesians. Its usage is often perceived as disrespectful and can be seen as a form of casual racism or xenophobia. \n\nThe term emerged as a shortened version of \"Indonesian\" but has taken on negative connotations over time. It is often used in a way that implies Indonesians are of lower social status or are viewed as less sophisticated. The term can carry undertones of prejudice and is generally considered inappropriate in polite conversation.\n\nIt's important to note that not all Malaysians or Singaporeans use this term, and many recognize it as offensive. Using someone's full nationality or ethnic description is always more respectful.",
